Assessment of Livelihood Vulnerability to Climate Change among Tribal Communities in Chhindwara and Dhar District, Central India
Amit Kumar, T Mohanasundari 
This study assesses the livelihood vulnerability of tribal households to climate change impacts in Chhindwara and Dhar districts of Central India, using a sample of 535 respondents and climatic data from the India Meteorological Department spanning 1954 to 2023. Nature
It employs a mixed-methods approach — innovative trend analysis for climatic pattern shifts, the Standardised Precipitation Index (SPI-1) for wet/dry conditions, the LVI-IPCC framework applied to survey data, and Multiple Linear Regression (MLR) to determine vulnerability drivers. Nature
The findings emphasize that tribal populations are particularly vulnerable to environmental stresses like unpredictable rainfall and temperature variations, which compromise agricultural output, water accessibility, and livelihood stability — especially given their dependence on rain-fed agriculture and natural resources. PubMed Central
The study recommends targeted interventions including investments in climate-resilient infrastructure, promoting sustainable livelihoods, and enhancing social protection, while integrating indigenous knowledge systems and fostering community-based adaptation.
